Infrastructure description

This infrastructure is a scaled-up version of a distributed web system designed to improve performance, scalability, and availability.

A user accesses the system using HTTPS, which ensures encrypted communication.

The infrastructure includes a cluster of load balancers (HAproxy). This provides high availability and failover support in case one load balancer fails.

Traffic is distributed from the load balancer cluster to a dedicated web server running Nginx. The web server handles HTTP requests and serves static content.

Requests requiring dynamic processing are forwarded to a separate application server, which executes the business logic of the application.

A dedicated database server is used to store and manage application data using MySQL.

Why additional elements are added
Load balancer cluster: to eliminate single point of failure and ensure high availability.
Separate web server: to handle HTTP requests efficiently and serve static content.
Separate application server: to process business logic independently.
Separate database server: to isolate data storage and improve performance.
Component separation explanation
Web server handles incoming HTTP requests and static content.
Application server handles business logic and dynamic processing.
Database server handles data storage and queries.

Separating these components improves scalability, performance, and system maintainability.
